title: Episode IV: A New Hope
description: The movie that started it all. Luke Skywalker is a young moisture farmer with a great destiny ahead as he journeys into space to save the princess and get the Empire's evil plans into the hands of the heroic terrorist group known as the Rebel Alliance.
review: You don't care what I think about this one. I'll spare you.

title: Episode V: Empire Strikes Back
description: In this sequel the Empire strikes back! Oh; you already knew that? Okay; well Lando's in this one. So that's cool.

title: Episode VI: Return of the Jedi
description: The thrilling conclusion of the Star Wars saga (until extended universe novels dealt with what happens after this movie; and then Disney acquired the franchise and decided this wasn't the end).

title: Episode I: The Phantom Menace
description: The fourth Star Wars movie; but the first episode; because George Lucas said so. This is the beginning of the prequel trilogy; taking place in a time of relative peace when Jedi numbered in the thousands and the Sith had been eradicated. Oh wait; there's a Sith... Uh oh.
review: Everyone's got their opinions about the prequels. Here's mine: don't think too hard about the plot; and this is a pretty fun movie. Whether or not the scene takes too long; pod racing is cool. I dressed up as Darth Maul for halloween several years when I was a kid. Jar Jar is terrible; a lot of the CGI has not aged super well; and kid Anakin is about what you'd expect from a kid actor (before Stranger Things upped our expectations). BUT - and hear me out here - Duel of Fates.

title: Episode II: Attack of the Clones
description: This is the move that comes after episode I and before episode III.
review: I don't really have much to say about this movie other than this is the movie after I and before episode III.

title: Episode III: Revenge of the Sith
description: The thrilling preclusion... wait that doesn't mean conclusion of prequels; but pretend it does. It's the last movie of the prequel trilogy. A lot of people like this one best of the prequels. I was always more of a Phantom Menace kinda guy; but I will admit that this one has the best Anakin hair.

title: The Clone Wars
description: Computer animated move which serves as a prologue for the TV series of the same name.
review: Is it good? No. But is the Clone Wars TV series good? I think so (eventually; anyways). You can skip this and just watch the series; though. All you need to know is Anakin got a padawan named Ahsoka. There; I saved you an hour and 38 minutes... You're still going to watch it anyways; because you're a completionist and that's why you downloaded this app; aren't you? *sigh* Don't say I didn't try.

title: Downfall of a Droid
description: Anakin gets shot down in a skirmish against General Grievous' fleet. R2-D2 appears lost and Anakin goes searching for him while trying to learn to work with R2's replacement.

title: Clone Cadets
description: The Domino squad is having trouble making progress in their training. Can they come together to pass the test and become fully fledged soldiers?

title: Supply Lines
description: Senator Organa and Representative Binks meet with the king of Toydaria to try to negotiate the use of that neutral planet as a staging ground to bring relief supplies to the war-torn Ryloth. Meanwhile; Jedi Master Ima-Gun Di and his clone battalion work to buy the Twi'leks of Ryloth time to escape an encroaching droid army.

title: A Sunny day in the Void
The Jedi Who Knew Too Much
The Machine in the Ghost
description: The ghost in on the run from several TIE fighters. While Hera flies and Kanan mans the blasters; it's up to Chopper to do...everything else.

title: Art Attack

title: Entanglement

title: Property of Ezra Bridger
description: Ezra sees a TIE fighter get shot down by a odified VCX-100 light freighter. He proceeds to "help" the pilot of the downed TIE.

title: Kanan #03
description: Young Caleb Dume is surrounded in his stolen ship above Coruscant. He must make a break for it; but where can he go when the whole galaxy is hunting him?

title: Dark Disciple

title: Servants of the Empire: Imperial Justice
Lando #1
description: Lando's putting the charm on hard to settle a debt. When he comes up a little short; it's time to plan a heist. A simple enough job stealing some Imperial scum's property. It's probably not important who that idiot Imperial is...right?

title: Kanan #04
description: The young padawan formerly known as Caleb Dume has been sold out... or has he? He must escape and continue to evade Commander Grey and Captain Stylez; his former one trooper allies.

title: Star Wars #07

title: Darth Vader #08
description: Aphra and the bounty hunters she hired pull a heist on an imperial light cruiser. Of course; there is more to this heist than meets the eye.

title: Lando #2
description: Having stolen the Imperialus; one of Emperor Palpatine's personal ships; all Lando and his crew have to do is escape the gravity well and hit hyperspace. Until three star destroyers show up and get in the way; of course.

title: Kanan #05
description: Commander Grey and Captain Styles have finally caught the Jedi traitor known as Caleb Dume. Is this the end for him? (This comic is an extended flashback; so the answer is kind of obvious.)

title: Star Wars #08

title: Lando #3

title: Lost Stars
description: This follows Thane Kyrell and Ciena Ree; two childhood friends from the outer rim; as they take part in the galactic civil war of Episodes IV-VI. They enlist as together as officers in the Imperial Navy and are thrilled to work on such a magnificent battle station. Until the events of Episode IV causes one of them to defect to the Rebel Alliance. This book follows these characters through all of the main events of Episodes IV; V; and VI; and slightly beyond to the battle of Jakku.
review: Let's just start by saying that Claudia Gray is one of the best authors in the new canon. This was the first book I read when I decided to explore the new canon; and I'm so glad I did. You don't need to know anything beyond what happens in the original trilogy to thoroughly enjoy this book. I would definitely recommend this as a first read for anyone curious about reading Star Wars novels.

title: Episode VII: The Force Awakens
description: The first movie of the third trilogy of the main movie saga which is the seventh movie made but...also the seventh movie in the series. Oh hey; they finally made the episode numbers line up. Anyways; this is the first movie after Disney acquired the Star Wars franchise. Rey; Finn; Poe; and the Resistance are the heroes. Kylo Ren; Hux; Phasma; Snoke; and the First Order are the bad guys. How did the First Order acquire so much power under the New Republic's nose in the thirty years since the end of Episode VI? Where did they get all their funding? I don't know; Helen.
review: The sequel trilogy is kind of divisive; but I like them.

title: Ahsoka
description: This book follows Ahsoka sometime after order 66. The audiobook is narrated by Ashley Eckstein; who voiced Ahsoka in The Clone Wars.
review: This is a book that will appeal to anyone who watched The Clone Wars; as it explains her fate following the series. I personally enjoyed seeing a more mature version of her than what we see in most of TCW. It would also be good for those who have watched Rebels as there is a run-in with an inquisitor; and a few other reasons that I don't want to spoil. I definitely had a lot of fun watching dots being connected between the two shows. If you haven't watched either show; then I'd say you could probably pass on this book (at least until you watch one of those shows).

description: You know about the Death Star; right? No? What are you even doing here? I don't mean to gatekeep; but why do you even have this app if you don't know what the Death Star is? Go watch Episode IV; and come back if you liked it... Did you watch it? That was pretty cool; huh? Anyways; they explain how they got the plans for the Death Star in this one. That may not have been a burning question you had; but here's your answer.
review: I know you're thinking "Surely the movie about a young Han Solo is the better Empire-era spinoff movie;" but it's not. This one is better. In fact; this one is better than several of the main-series movies. I'll let you decide which main-series movies this one is better than; but it is definitely better than at least one.

description: We meet the 204th; also known as Shadow Wing; a squadron of pilots who are good at what they do. Which is shooting down rebel scum. Their next mission is to assist a Star Destroyer that has gone out of contact. Should be easy; right?

title: Dooku: Jedi Lost
description: Dooku: Jedi Lost follows the story of Dooku from his time as a Jedi Initiate through his departure from the Jedi Order. It's told through flashbacks as Asajj Ventress learns about his history. It ties into Master & Apprentice a little bit; as the character of Rael Aveross appears in both.
review: I thought it was interesting to see Dooku's youth; and to see his motivations. It was enjoyable; but ultimately I'm not sure I found this as an adequate explanation for who he became. This explores some of the ethical questions regarding of the nature of the Jedi Order; which I always want to explore more. As it is only available in audiobook; it is worth noting that the voice of Dooku doesn't sound at all like Sir Christopher Lee; which I found distracting and disappointing. Otherwise; the voice acting is generally pretty good. All of the other characters that have previous on-screen appearances (Asajj; Yoda; Qui-Gon; etc.) all have well-approximated voices. I particularly enjoyed young Qui-Gon Jinn; although it may have sounded just a bit silly.

title: Star Wars Adventures Free Comic Book Day 2019
Age of Rebellion: Jabba the Hutt #1
Alphabet Squadron
description: This novel takes place sometime after the battle of Endor (Episode VI) and before the battle of Jakku. It follows a rag-tag group (but the author is good enough to never refers to the group as rag-tag (show don't tell; y'all)) that comes together for the purpose of bringing down a Tie Fighter squad known as Shadow Wing. This novel ties in with the Tie Fighter comics.
review: Just wow. I really really liked this book a lot. The characters are unique; interesting; and believable. If you're at all into the whole starfighter aspect of the Star Wars universe; or are curious about what happened after Episode VI; then this is a must-read. Otherwise; it's still a must-read.
